The system integrates with a third-party API that enforces a strict rate limit of 3 requests per second.
However, during peak hours, the platform generates more than 20 requests per second across 25 customers.

This leads to:

API failures (null responses)
Unreliable system behavior

The goal is to design a system that:

Ensures rate limit compliance (≤ 3 req/sec)
Handles high incoming traffic
Maintains fairness across customers
Handles failures gracefully
Architecture Design
 Components Used

I designed the system using components already present in the existing tech stack:

Django API → Receives incoming requests
Redis → Acts as a message queue and temporary storage
Celery Workers → Process queued requests asynchronously
Scheduler Layer → Ensures fair distribution of requests
External API → Third-party service with rate limit

 Architecture Flow
Client sends request to Django API
Instead of directly calling external API, request is pushed to Redis queue
Separate queues are maintained per customer
A scheduler picks requests from queues in a fair manner
Celery worker processes requests at a controlled rate
Request is sent to external API
Response is returned and stored if needed
